WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.000
George Stagg, Senior Software Engineer, Open Source Team, WebR Project

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:40.000
and a piece of software called ShinyLive that Winston and others from Posit Air were working on around the same time as I started working on webR.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:52.000
So yes, running Shiny without a server, but one thing we've realised talking to people about this kind of thing is that we're not always clear about what we mean by the word server.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:01:09.000
What is a server anyhow? And really, one way to define what a server is, is a machine connected to the internet that runs 24-7, 365 days a year and it runs your Shiny app and serves it to people.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:23.000
And this is a sort of pictorial representation of that. You have your R or Python server if you're using Shiny for Python. It sits there and services requests from clients who connect with a web browser.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Now there are more complicated topologies that can happen. So for example, your R or Python code could be running on a server that's behind another web server that handles web requests.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Or you could have something like an internal network or proxying or firewalls and all that kind of stuff. But really, fundamentally, it looks more like this.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:53.000
At some point, you have a machine that is running an R session or a Python session and in that session is running Shiny and that's what's servicing your users' apps.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Now, there are some good solutions for running a Shiny server already. If you're a place that works with on-premises Shiny servers, there's a few options there on the screen.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:20.000
At the simplest, you might simply have a laptop or a desktop that sits and runs RStudio. And one of the things RStudio can do is if you're developing Shiny apps, there's a preview button, you click that and you can see your app.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:34.000
What's happening underneath is that RStudio is starting a Shiny server for you and your machine is opening a web browser, which may or may not be built into RStudio, and then loading that app.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And in that case, your client machine and your server machine are the same. And it can do that because your workstation or laptop that you're working with is quite powerful. It can do both of those things at the same time.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Now, the problem with that is what happens when you want to start sharing your Shiny app with people? Running your Shiny app on your machine is not a good place for that. It's not very scalable.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:10.000
So, the next step up in terms of scalability or enterprise-ready Shiny apps may be something like a server or a virtual machine sitting in a rack on-premises running a piece of software called Shiny Server, which is free and open source.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:26.000
You can download that and run it without paying a positive penny. And again, that might service, who knows, maybe 10 users, maybe more, 20, 50, who knows. It depends on your app, right? It depends on how much computational resources your app uses.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:34.000
But eventually, you're going to reach a point where if you try sharing your app with too many people at the same time, it's going to start struggling under the load.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:41.000
And when that happens, then you have to start thinking about more enterprise solutions, the idea of scalability and reliability of your app.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:55.000
And that's where software that's more paid for, like Posit Connect or other offerings, come into play, where you have a more enterprise solution so that your app is reliable and can be accessed by many users and scales for that reason.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:02.000
And these are all on-premises solutions. It all ranges from very casual to very enterprise.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
But not everyone has on-premises hosting. There's also cloud hosting, and this is a similar story.

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:16.000
You could start by servicing a few users on ShinyOps.io, and there's a free tier that can service certain numbers of people.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:24.000
And as you get more enterprise, there's now Posit on Hugging Face available, and then there's the big cloud services like Amazon, Google, Microsoft.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:30.000
Now, what you find is that generally people will fall into two camps.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:40.000
Either they'll be a very casual user with very few end users using their app, and they can usually get away with something like ShinyServer or ShinyOps.io is very popular.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:46.000
And at the other end of the spectrum, you end up with big enterprise apps that could have hundreds or even thousands of users.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:54.000
And in that case, those users will be able to and willing to pay for enterprise-level software with enterprise-level support.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:00.000
However, there is one group of people that kind of sit in between and don't fall into either camp.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
And I used to be one of them.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
They're academics, people teaching.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:17.000
They will often have 50, 100, 150 people maybe trying to use a Shiny app at the same time or some kind of R server, and yet not necessarily have access to those enterprise-level solutions.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:28.000
Something like maybe their company just hasn't bought or had a contract with Posit to have something like Workbench or Posit Cloud.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:34.000
Or maybe just their institution, the department, just doesn't have the money.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.000
I mean, it happens.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:50.000
So in that case, there is that group of people, usually academics, who want to use Shiny apps, and they want to service those apps to hundreds of people, but they can't because they don't have the computational load available to them.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:57.000
There is one solution to this kind of thing, and academics like to do this kind of thing, which is static web hosting.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:18.000
So you can actually, for free, put educational content or any web content, really, that's static, onto places like GitHub pages, Netify, Cloud for Web pages, or even QuartoPub has a free publishing platform where if you write a Quarto document, you can upload that Quarto document to QuartoPub for free and get a URL to share with your friends.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:22.000
If you haven't used Quarto before, by the way, it's kind of like the new R Markdown.

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:23.000
It's brilliant.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:25.000
Do give it a go.

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.000
I'll be talking more about Quarto later.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.000
But there's an issue with this form of hosting.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.000
It's great because it's sort of abstracted away.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
You don't have to think about the service anymore.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:38.000
The people who run these services, they think about the service.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:44.000
You just think about your files and put them, give them to the service, and they will service them for you.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:45.000
They'll host them for you.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
But it doesn't work with Shiny apps.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:54.000
And the reason it doesn't work with Shiny apps is explicitly because it's static web hosting.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And that's why it's so cheap and scales so well, because those files, they're fixed.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:06:59.000
They don't change.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
You just give them to a user, and they display them on the screen.

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.000
That's what static web hosting means.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:09.000
And in particular, it means that you can't have any dynamic R or Python code running on a server.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
That's just not how static hosting works.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.000
But wouldn't it be great if we could run Shiny apps using static hosting?

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
And that's what Shiny Live does.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:24.000
Shiny Live was announced originally last year.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And it's a way of running Shiny apps so that the client-side browser actually runs that Shiny R process or Python process in the web browser.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:42.000
So all you need to be able to run those apps is one of these static web servers that just gives you the files and says, run this in your browser.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.000
And when it works, it works absolutely brilliantly.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:51.000
Python's been around a while, and Shiny Live for R was released just last month.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:54.000
It was announced at PositConf by Joe.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:04.000
So what's happening here is that we're kind of taking advantage of the fact that these computers themselves have computational abilities.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:11.000
They're quite performant, and they have that ability to run the server and the client on the same machine, just like that RStudio desktop.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:17.000
And that's what this architecture of Shiny Live takes advantage of.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:24.000
Back in the old days, before my time of computing, this kind of thing couldn't be done.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
It was more like the traditional Shiny architecture, where you have a big server.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:35.000
In the 60s, you'd have machines like this, an IBM mainframe that would take up an entire room, or maybe even earlier than this, an entire building.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
And instead of working directly in that room, you'd work on one of these machines.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.000
This is called a teletype.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And there may be several teletypes within the building that all connect to that mainframe.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:51.000
And those teletypes, they're a bit like that web browser client, and the IBM mainframe is a bit like the server.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So it's an old architecture.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:55.000
I mean, it works well.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:00.000
I mean, even into the 70s and 80s, these teletypes, they were replaced with computer monitors.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:03.000
But they were called dumb terminals, because they didn't think.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:05.000
They just connected to a remote machine.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
But everybody these days is probably carrying a device like this in their pocket.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:13.000
Or if not, they'll have something like a laptop with them.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:16.000
Or at the very least, a desktop that they can connect to.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:24.000
And there's all this computational power available to all of us that we just wouldn't be able to use without something like ShinyLive.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:27.000
So being able to take advantage of this, I think, is a real benefit.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:32.000
So how does this work, technically?

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:35.000
Because, you know, I showed a picture of a phone.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.000
You can't have R installed onto a phone.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
So there's something magical going on here that makes this work.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:49.000
The main technical detail that allows this to actually happen is something called WebAssembly, which was released in 2017.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.000
The technical description of what this is is a portable binary code format.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:03.000
And what that means is that traditionally, code, when you compile it to run on a machine, needs to be compiled for that specific type of machine.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:08.000
So you'll have a piece of code, and you'll compile it for a Windows machine that's a normal laptop.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:14.000
Or you'll compile it for a Mac machine, or a Windows machine, or even a phone or a tablet.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:19.000
And these are all producing what's called binary format, the output of compilation.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:24.000
The code that the CPU actually runs, they're all different, depending on the machine you're running on.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
With WebAssembly, that's not true.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:33.000
Because what happens is that that output, which is called a binary, doesn't just run on the machine, but it runs inside a web browser.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
And most machines have a web browser.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:40.000
And the web browser understands that code format.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:46.000
So what you do is you compile your code once, and it will run anywhere, anywhere with a web browser that supports WebAssembly.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
That's what portable means.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
And it's surprisingly good.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:55.000
You'd expect that this kind of thing would enact a performance impact.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:59.000
And it does, but it's much less than you would expect.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:04.000
You really can have high-performance applications running inside web pages with WebAssembly.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:09.000
There are even games that you can play through a web browser without installing anything to your machine.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
It's really quite impressive.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
And most modern browsers support it.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
Chrome, Firefox, and Safari all support it.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
There are other benefits to using WebAssembly.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
There is security implications.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:27.000
Code that runs inside WebAssembly runs inside a container and is sandboxed.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:35.000
And it inherits all of the years of work of security that web browsers provide.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.000
Another benefit of WebAssembly is something called numerical reproducibility.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:53.000
So this is important, particularly for scientific or statistical applications, because there are algorithms that's known as what's called unstable.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
And that means they're very sensitive to changes in the numbers.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:06.000
Different computers will actually compute numerical algorithms slightly differently because of something called floating point numbers.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.000
Which comes about because computers can't represent every number.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:11.000
You know, there's an infinite number of them.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
It can't represent all of them.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
So what happens is it has to do approximations.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
And those approximations are slightly different depending on what machine you run your algorithm on.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:24.000
And therefore, eventually, the algorithm can give you different answers.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:25.000
And that's not reproducible.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
That's kind of bad science, right?

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:36.000
So what WebAssembly does is one of the things it implements is a strict set of instructions for how floating point numbers should be calculated.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:43.000
So there are certain guarantees about numerical reproducibility of algorithms that you don't get with normal compiled software.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
So that's a nice bonus that WebAssembly provides.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:55.000
The way that generally people use WebAssembly these days is either, some people will write it directly, but that's really rare.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
It's not designed to be written.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:00.000
It's more designed to be compiled to as a target.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.000
There are Rust compilers to convert Rust code into WebAssembly.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.000
But the compiler that I'm particularly interested in is something called Inscripten.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
And Inscripten is magical.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.000
It's brilliant.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:22.000
Because what it does is allows you to take some C or C++ code that's written for Linux and instead compile a WebAssembly binary using that code.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
And it provides a sort of Linux-like environment.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:26.000
It's been around for a few years.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
It actually predates WebAssembly.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.000
I first saw Inscripten in about 2014, I think.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:36.000
Back then, it didn't use WebAssembly, but it still worked really, really well.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And it's used for a few different projects.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
So there's SQLite, FFmpeg, DOSBox.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:47.000
These things can all run in the browser because they're using Inscripten to compile that C code into WebAssembly code.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:54.000
Now, the full process goes kind of like this.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:00.000
There are programming languages like Python and R that are written in C or C++.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.000
Their interpreters that read the input code are written in these languages.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
So, well, we'll just give that to Inscripten.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:08.000
Produce a WebAssembly binary.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.000
Job done.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:10.000
Off to the pub.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
But it's not that easy.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:20.000
It's actually quite difficult because of restrictions that WebAssembly code runs under in the browser.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:28.000
So, for example, you can't open local files or any network sockets from inside WebAssembly.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:33.000
And that's a shame because things like R, you can do read.csv and give it a URL.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
And it will download that data for you.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:36.000
And that's really nice.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
So that's a shame.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
Threading and forking is difficult in WebAssembly.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
There's no native threading instructions.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:51.000
Graphics and font support is a bit difficult because WebAssembly doesn't have access to something called the JavaScript DOM.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
So you have to kind of work around that.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:56.000
And probably the biggest problem is legacy code.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:00.000
It turns out that with these programming languages, it's not all C or C++.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:08.000
There is code from 1972 or whatever that does a numerical algorithm that has been around for years and nobody's touched.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
Written in something like Fortran.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:16.000
I've done my fair share of hacking at Fortran 77 code just to get WebR running.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:18.000
And you have to support these things.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:22.000
They've been around for a long time and they're a core part of the language.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:24.000
So that's quite difficult.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.000
It makes things harder than it really needs to be.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
But it looks like Unix.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
It looks like a Linux environment.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
But there are browser security limitations.

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:51.000
And the trick with things like this is to replace those older pieces of code with new pieces of code that use browser APIs that allow you to access networks or download files or show graphics on the screen in a safe and secure way.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:53.000
That's the game.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:55.000
And it works.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:58.000
PyDyed is a port of Python to WebAssembly.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
It's been around a little while, longer than WebR.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:05.000
And you can install and run certain Python packages in a web browser.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:14.000
It supports a fair few packages, including the scientific stack of Matplotlib and Numbers and Pandas and various other packages.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
It works really, really well.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:24.000
And maybe two years ago at this point, I remember seeing PyDyed, trying it out and being blown away by being able to run Python in a web browser.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:25.000
I thought that was brilliant.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
But there was no equivalent for R.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.000
And I kind of needed this because I was teaching at the time.

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:32.000
And I had students.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
It was just as COVID was kicking off.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
And they didn't have access to a computer cluster anymore.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:38.000
They would have their own devices.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:39.000
And they'd have something like an iPad.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
And they were doing all their work on an iPad.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
And I was like, well, how am I going to install RStudio onto an iPad?

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
We didn't have PositCloud or RStudio Cloud at the time.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
We didn't have access to anything like that.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.000
So I thought, well, there must be some way to make this work.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.000
It works for Python.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:54.000
It must work for R.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:56.000
So I made WebR.

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
It's a version of the R interpreter that's built for WebAssembly.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:05.000
And it allows you to execute R code directly in a web browser without supporting R server.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:08.000
That's because the R process runs directly in your web browser.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:15.000
For techie people who know about these kind of things, it does support Node.js to run R code server side.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:22.000
And it is being used, for example, by the R Universe team to run certain things server side with WebR.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:29.000
But really, we're focusing mainly on the front end, running R in a browser.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:31.000
That's mainly what we're focusing on.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:34.000
So, yeah.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:38.000
I'm going to talk about running Shiny with WebR a little bit later.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
But before I do that, I just want to talk a little bit more about WebR itself.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
And the kind of things that you can do with WebR without necessarily using Shiny.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.000
So this is a screenshot of what I've called the WebR demo application.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:56.000
What this is, it's an IDE running in the web browser with an R session.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
Now, I should say, I actually lied.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:00.000
This isn't really a screenshot.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:01.000
This is a live session.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
So I can actually interact with it.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:09.000
And this is one of the real benefits of web software in general, is that web software is very interconnected.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:14.000
You can plug things together very easily and communicate over this sort of universal language called JavaScript.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
And this is an iframe.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:21.000
So it's embedded into a set of slides, which are browser-based, written by Quarto.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Quarto created these slides.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
So this is a real R session.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:31.000
I can get some numbers, do some random numbers, and access the console at the bottom left-hand side of the screen there.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
And I actually have graphics as well.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
So let's do some demographics.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
And that was very quick.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:48.000
But over on the bottom right-hand side of the screen here, we have a way of plotting things in WebR and looking at the results.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
And you can download these images.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
There's a button to save that plot.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:56.000
In the top left-hand side of the screen is a code editor.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:59.000
This is powered by a piece of software called CodeMirror.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:01.000
So it's very good.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:03.000
It allows you to type R codes.

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.000
So let's do foo equals function.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:10.000
And you can see that I get autocomplete, powered by R itself.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.000
R has autocomplete built in.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:18.000
And because we're running R directly in this page, we can just plug into that to get suggestions.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
Live coding always goes well.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.000
We'll see.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.000
How well did I do?

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.000
Pretty good.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:35.000
I'm happy with that.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:38.000
So yeah, you can write R code and run it.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:39.000
And you can actually save these files.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:43.000
If I hit save, you'll see that it appears in the top right-hand side of the screen.

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.000
And this is a virtual file system.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.000
And this is provided by Enscripten.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
It kind of looks like a Unix, Linux file system.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:51.000
But it's transit.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:52.000
It lives in the browser.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:57.000
And it's not actually accessing your local files, which makes it very secure, yet very flexible.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:01.000
And you can upload files to this virtual file system or download files.

00:20:01.000 --> 00:20:03.000
And you can do all sorts of things.

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.000
And one final thing.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
I'll just open some help file.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:11.000
And this will take a little while, because those help files aren't actually downloaded until you ask for them.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:14.000
So this may or may not load, depending on Wi-Fi.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:19.000
But the idea is that you can ask for help within R.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:20.000
And there it is.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:21.000
The help page will appear.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
And you can use it as normal.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:27.000
So I should say this is kind of superficial.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
If you've used RStudio before, you can get a squint.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:32.000
It's kind of like RStudio in a browser.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:36.000
But I will caveat this by saying it's way less featured.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:39.000
It looks good, but this is really it.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:43.000
No one's going to be doing serious package development in this kind of software.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:48.000
It's a demo of what WebR can do when running in a web browser.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:53.000
But one thing I think is clear is that there's enough there to do the basics of data science.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:59.000
You could teach someone how to load some data, wrangle it with something like dply, and then make some plots.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.000
The basics are there.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:04.000
And that makes it very good for teaching, in my opinion.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.000
So the URL for that is at the top of the screen if you want to try that at some point.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:08.000
It's there.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:09.000
You can use it.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.000
It's free.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:17.000
Another useful thing for WebR is a quarter extension that I didn't actually write.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:19.000
Someone else wrote.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:21.000
James Balamuto wrote this.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:30.000
But the idea is that you can write a document in quarto and have these runnable code blocks that you can edit your R code on the fly.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
Click a button and see the results.

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:43.000
You can imagine this is really useful for teaching because it means that if a student or a learner is on a page and is taught an algorithm or how to use a piece of R code,

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:45.000
they can click that button and see the results immediately.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:46.000
And they can experiment.

00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:48.000
They can change things and they don't break anything.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:51.000
And they can see what the results are immediately.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:54.000
The important thing here, I think, is the lack of context switching.

00:21:54.000 --> 00:22:01.000
What you don't have is changing to a different window or opening RStudio and typing the code and copying and pasting and then pointing this out.

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:03.000
Oh, you've got to read this bit of the screen.

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:04.000
You don't have any of that.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:05.000
It's just there directly in the page.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:10.000
And that reduction in context switching, I think, is really important.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:11.000
And it's not just documents.

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:14.000
It works in slides.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:16.000
It is going to work in slides, which is good.

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:19.000
So if you want to try this out, download quarto.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:23.000
If you've used R Markdown before, you'll get started with quarto quite easily.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:24.000
It's Markdown based.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.000
And all you have to do is install this extension.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:36.000
And then if you want to add a runnable code block, there's this WebR-R type of code block that you can just put straight in there.

00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:39.000
And if you're in slides, it will look like this.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.000
And again, this is live and runnable.

00:22:41.000 --> 00:22:45.000
So imagine I'm teaching a workshop or a lecture.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.000
I can run the code to get the results and edit it.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:53.000
You know, a student might ask me, you know, what happens if I remove the word island from group by?

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:58.000
Well, I can try it out and just get directly on the screen there.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
Or I could do something completely different.

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:06.000
I could delete all of this and just run any R code I want because it's a real R session.

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:11.000
Now, if you've used something like LearnR before, you may have seen this kind of thing before.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:15.000
But LearnR is a bit different in that it relies on a shiny server running somewhere.

00:23:15.000 --> 00:23:25.000
While this is completely statically hosted, you can put this on something like GitHub Pages and you don't need to run that shiny server.

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:30.000
And again, these quarto blocks, they run with graphics as well.

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:36.000
So this is actually using a ggplot and putting it directly into the slides as I talk.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:40.000
And again, someone might ask me, oh, what happens if you remove the aesthetics to this plot?

00:23:40.000 --> 00:23:43.000
Well, you can do it live and find out.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:46.000
And it turns out it makes it go black and white.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.000
So it's really nice.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:23:53.000
The way the graphics work in WebR is a bit different from normal.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:24:02.000
It actually has something called a graphics device that reimplements the primitive drawing commands of R for a web browser.

00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:06.000
It uses something called the JavaScript Canvas API.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:17.000
And this is really good because what it allows us to do is take advantage of features that exist in a web browser in our R plotting routines.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:22.000
So this is an R plot that's designed to show off the internationalization features of WebR.

00:24:22.000 --> 00:24:25.000
And you can see we've got some Japanese text, so it's a different font.

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:30.000
We've got some, I think that's Arabic and Hebrew, I think.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.000
And those are interesting because they're written right to left.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:37.000
And surprisingly, this doesn't always work.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:40.000
Even in native R installations, this is actually quite difficult to get right.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:44.000
You need to download packages to, in some cases, to make this work.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:47.000
So the fact that this is running in the browser and just works is really brilliant.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:56.000
And again, that's taking advantage of the years of text rendering features that have been built into web browsers over the years.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:07.000
I particularly like the Arabic example because it depends very heavily on ligatures, which doesn't always work well when you're trying to do text rendering.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.000
So the fact that this works is nice.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:19.000
And also because it's using a browser API instead of running it fully in WebAssembly, you can actually take advantage of all the fonts that already exist on the user system.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:21.000
Now, this is not my laptop, so this may not work.

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
But the joke was going to be that you can even use cursed fonts.

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:30.000
So if you really want to, let's see if it's installed.

00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:32.000
It's not installed.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:33.000
Good job, Clarissa.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:37.000
But that does work on my laptop.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:38.000
So yeah, emojis work.

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:48.000
Any kind of font that exists on your local system, that will be able to be loaded by WebR using these extensions, which is really nice.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:52.000
I think this might be the last example of what WebR can do without Shiny.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:56.000
But as I mentioned before, web frameworks plug into each other really nicely.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:02.000
One of the things you can do is use WebR with other frameworks that exist on the web.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:04.000
So you may not want to use Shiny.

00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:08.000
You may be a web developer, and you're used to something called Observable.

00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:13.000
And this is just a piece of code that does a plot using Observable.js.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:17.000
So if you've programmed in Observable before, this should be very familiar.

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:26.000
But the idea is that what you can do is get some data from R, do some analysis in R, which is very good at that,

00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:31.000
and then plot an interactive plot in the web browser using frameworks that are very good at that.

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:38.000
And you can plug these things together with minimal fuss and get nice interactive plots with relatively few lines of code.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:41.000
Packages are supported.

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:49.000
So what we can do is compile packages, but they must be compiled especially for WebAssembly.

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:54.000
What you can't do is use normal R packages in WebR.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:57.000
They have to be pre-compiled to work in this WebAssembly environment.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:04.000
And you can't install packages directly and build them within WebR because there's no compiler available in the web browser.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:10.000
But we've built as many packages as we can, and we have a repository, which lives up here.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:16.000
And we have about 50% of CRAN-built packages that you can try out.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:19.000
Now, I haven't tried all of these. They could be broken.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:22.000
These are just packages that compile without any errors.

00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:25.000
But the ones I've tried have pretty much all worked.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:29.000
So if you do have an R package you'd like to try with WebR, come talk to me.

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:32.000
We'll give it a go and find out if it works.

00:27:33.000 --> 00:27:36.000
Some examples of useful packages that are available.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.000
There's the tidyverse and tidymodels.

00:27:40.000 --> 00:27:43.000
It takes a little while to load because there's quite a few packages.

00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:45.000
But they do, the core packages load.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:48.000
Not all of tidyverse is available.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:52.000
The packages such as httr, I think, are part of tidyverse.

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:55.000
But they won't work because they depend on network access,

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:59.000
which is, as I say, very limited in WebAssembly for security reasons.

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:02.000
So those packages won't work yet.

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:05.000
But, in theory, they could be replaced with browser APIs.

00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:08.000
And the core packages for tidyverse do work.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:11.000
Geospatial packages are available.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:13.000
And, again, this will take a little while to run

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:16.000
just because it's downloading packages in the background.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:20.000
But what this does is do a plot of a map.

00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:22.000
So this is a plot of the US.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:24.000
And, again, these packages, like the sf package,

00:28:24.000 --> 00:28:27.000
is very big in geospatial statistics.

00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:32.000
And those geospatial packages depend on a big list of system libraries

00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:36.000
that normally would have to be compiled and installed to the local machine.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:38.000
And that can be tricky.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:41.000
It's not the easiest package in the world to set up on a new machine.

00:28:41.000 --> 00:28:44.000
But here it works because all of those packages

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:47.000
have been precompiled for WebAssembly.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
Databases are available as well.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:54.000
This is an example of running an SQLite SQL database.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:57.000
You can run some SQL code in R.

00:28:57.000 --> 00:28:59.000
So if you're teaching someone some SQL code,

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.000
you can do exactly the same thing as before.

00:29:01.000 --> 00:29:05.000
You can say, oh, what happens if I change my query to say that?

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:07.000
You can do that thing.

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:11.000
Those packages are available, which is, again, really useful.

00:29:11.000 --> 00:29:16.000
Connecting to remote databases will not work, again, for security reasons.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:21.000
But we have some ideas on how we can handle database connections

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:23.000
going forward in the future.

00:29:23.000 --> 00:29:25.000
Okay.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.000
Let me talk about Shiny.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:32.000
The way this works is that web browsers have a feature

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:34.000
called service workers.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:36.000
What service workers do, well, they do a few things.

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:38.000
But one of the important things that they do

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:42.000
is they can capture network traffic.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:46.000
So what you can do is when you open up a Shiny app in your machine,

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.000
what will happen in the background is the Shiny app will go,

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
oh, I need to connect to the Shiny server.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:54.000
I need to load, you know, johnswebsite.com,

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:57.000
colon, whatever port Shiny is running on, or whatever.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:00.000
There's a connection that happens in the background to a Shiny server.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:03.000
Service workers can intercept that connection

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:04.000
and say, no, don't go over there.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:06.000
Instead, go over here.

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:08.000
In fact, don't even go anywhere.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
Just run this piece of code.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:11.000
And that's what service workers do.

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:13.000
And that's how Shiny is able to run in WebR.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:17.000
What WebR will do is start a service worker

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:20.000
and capture that network traffic that would normally be sent to a Shiny server.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:23.000
And instead, rather than sending it over the network,

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:27.000
it will send it to a WebAssembly thread where WebR is running

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:30.000
and say, WebR, what would Shiny do if it was running on a server?

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:33.000
Give me the response that Shiny would give.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:35.000
And that's how that works.

00:30:35.000 --> 00:30:41.000
So what that allows you to do is run the Shiny server itself on the local machine.

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:47.000
The Shiny client can be opened in the web browser.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:49.000
And it looks and feels just like a normal Shiny client,

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.000
because as far as the Shiny client is concerned,

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:53.000
it really is connecting to a remote server.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:57.000
But the service worker allows that remote server

00:30:57.000 --> 00:31:00.000
to actually be running inside the browser.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:02.000
Now, you can set this up manually.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:04.000
It's a bit of a pain.

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:07.000
I do have a GitHub repo that explains how to do all this

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:10.000
and set up a static web server and Shiny in the background.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:14.000
But like I say, you really have to be a JavaScript developer

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:17.000
to really understand what's going on there.

00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
So instead, we use Shiny Live.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:22.000
And Shiny Live makes this much, much easier.

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:25.000
And it makes it easy enough that everyone in this room

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.000
could create their own serverless Shiny app.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:30.000
Even if you've never made a Shiny app before.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:32.000
I mean, Andre's workshop yesterday,

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:35.000
we had Shiny Live running for Shiny for Python.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:38.000
And we had people creating apps,

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.000
even though they'd never used Shiny for Python before,

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:43.000
directly in the web browser.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:48.000
I think anyone can do this with Shiny Live.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:50.000
And there's a few options.

00:31:50.000 --> 00:31:53.000
The first option is an online editor, which I'll show in a minute.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.000
That's what we were using yesterday.

00:31:55.000 --> 00:31:58.000
The second option is to take a Shiny app that already exists

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:01.000
and convert it into a Shiny Live app.

00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:04.000
And the third option, which I quite like as well,

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:09.000
is embedding a Shiny app into a quarter document or presentation.

00:32:09.000 --> 00:32:12.000
So the first option looks like this.

00:32:12.000 --> 00:32:16.000
There's an editor with some examples.

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:19.000
Let's see if I can open this in a new tab.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:22.000
How do I get out?

00:32:22.000 --> 00:32:25.000
Let's try F11. F11 was the answer.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:35.000
So this is a real Shiny app running in a web page

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:37.000
on the right-hand side here.

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:40.000
And there's an editor on the left-hand side

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:42.000
that you can change live

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:45.000
and rebuild your Shiny app directly in the web browser.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:46.000
And this is statically hosted.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:32:48.000
There is no Shiny server running anywhere

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:50.000
other than in your browser.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.000
And just to prove it's real, I can move that slider

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:54.000
and get some reactive results.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:56.000
And if I did want to change the app,

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:59.000
I could say, let's just put some Ys on Hello Shiny

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:01.000
and rebuild that app.

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:03.000
And it just appears straight away.

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.000
So you can actually build a Shiny app live

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:07.000
from practically nothing,

00:33:07.000 --> 00:33:10.000
very, very easily using this website.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:12.000
And there's a bunch of examples on there as well.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:17.000
So if you wanted to change to a different example,

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:20.000
these are the standard Shiny, R Shiny examples,

00:33:20.000 --> 00:33:23.000
you can do that and immediately see the results.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:26.000
So this is great for teaching Shiny.

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:30.000
As we learned yesterday, it works really, really well.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:38.000
That is just one way of using Shiny Live.

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:40.000
It's probably the easiest way to actually just get up

00:33:40.000 --> 00:33:43.000
and running to try it out.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:45.000
The nice thing about the Shiny Live app

00:33:45.000 --> 00:33:46.000
is that there's a share button.

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:48.000
So after you've edited your app in the web browser,

00:33:48.000 --> 00:33:49.000
it is transient.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.000
It doesn't save your changes.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:53.000
But there is a share button that gives you a URL

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:55.000
that you can then give to your friend.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:57.000
And then if your friend opens that URL,

00:33:57.000 --> 00:34:00.000
it will open in Shiny Live and run that app for you,

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:03.000
optionally with or without the editor component.

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:06.000
So you really could write your app in the browser,

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:08.000
give your friend the application URL,

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:10.000
which it does end up being quite long,

00:34:10.000 --> 00:34:13.000
but it works.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:18.000
You can just give that to your friend.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:21.000
The next option is to convert a Shiny app.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.000
I haven't done this very much.

00:34:23.000 --> 00:34:27.000
Barrett's the main developer of this R package,

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:30.000
but there is an R package, Shiny Live,

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:33.000
which allows you to take an app that exists already

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:36.000
and turn it into a Shiny Live app.

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:37.000
So there's a couple of commands there

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:39.000
that will install that package.

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:43.000
It's not on CRAN yet, but soon, soon.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:47.000
And then one line, Shiny Live export will take an app

00:34:47.000 --> 00:34:49.000
that exists in the myapp directory

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:51.000
and produce an output directory site,

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.000
which contains those static files.

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:56.000
And it can be really quite small.

00:34:56.000 --> 00:34:58.000
This is an example that I run,

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:00.000
and those files are there,

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:04.000
ready to be uploaded to some static web server service,

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:07.000
like GitHub Pages.

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:11.000
And all the Shiny Live service work is set up for you.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:13.000
You don't have to know how it works, really.

00:35:13.000 --> 00:35:17.000
You can just upload those files, and it should just work.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.000
If you want to preview the application,

00:35:19.000 --> 00:35:22.000
there's a function built into R that you can run,

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.000
and that will open a web browser

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:28.000
with that Shiny Live app loaded.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:32.000
The final way to use Shiny Live is the Quota extension.

00:35:32.000 --> 00:35:35.000
So again, there's a Quota command here

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:37.000
that will install the Shiny Live extension.

00:35:37.000 --> 00:35:39.000
Then once you've done that, what it allows you to do

00:35:39.000 --> 00:35:41.000
is in the middle of your Quota document,

00:35:41.000 --> 00:35:44.000
literally just write a Shiny app

00:35:44.000 --> 00:35:47.000
with the right code block type,

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:50.000
and that Shiny app will be automatically converted

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:53.000
into a Shiny Live app and embedded into your document.

00:35:53.000 --> 00:35:57.000
And you really can just write your app directly into the page,

00:35:57.000 --> 00:36:00.000
and it will do it for you.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:03.000
Oh, almost everything worked.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.000
This is a Shiny app. I'll tell you what I'll do.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:08.000
I'll switch laptops real quick.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:13.000
I've only got five minutes, but I'll try my best.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:27.000
It's worth it, I promise.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:31.000
So this is a Shiny Live app

00:36:31.000 --> 00:36:34.000
that's running in my Quota presentation,

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
and it was embedded into the page

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
directly using that method I just showed.

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
It was written in the slides

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:44.000
and made available on the page.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:46.000
Again, just to prove that this is a real Shiny app,

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:50.000
what this is doing is producing some random numbers,

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.000
and if you increase the number of samples,

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:57.000
it should approach some limiting distribution there.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
So if you want to create Shiny Live apps,

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:04.000
I recommend the online editor and the Quota extension.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:07.000
They're both very good.

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:11.000
And other than that, I think I'll just put some caveats.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
I'll just say Shiny Live is experimental.

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
Things might change,

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:17.000
and we are working on making package loading quicker.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:20.000
Part of the problem today was just that packages for R

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:22.000
are just quite large,

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:24.000
and they take a while to download on Wi-Fi and load,

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:26.000
so we're working on making that quicker.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.000
And finally, one last thing to say

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:30.000
is that there's no secrets with a Shiny Live app.

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:33.000
When your Shiny Live app is available for users,

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:36.000
they will be able to see the entire source code of your app.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:38.000
That's just the way it works.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:41.000
So if you have things like secret tokens or even passwords,

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:43.000
don't put passwords in your Shiny apps.

00:37:43.000 --> 00:37:45.000
But if you do, definitely don't make a Shiny Live app,

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.000
because it will be available to read

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:49.000
by anyone who loads the page, so bear that in mind.

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.000
Yep, there's some URLs. Give it a go.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
And thank you very much for listening.

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
APPLAUSE

